                        Nagʷadgʷād</t:placeName>

                    <t:country ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3010Ethiop">ʾItyoṗyā</t:country>
                    <t:region notBefore="1991" type="RegionalState" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1426Amhara">ʾAmharā kǝllǝl</t:region>
                    <t:region notAfter="1974" type="province" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6185Wallo">Wallo</t:region>
                    <t:settlement type="zone" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC6572SouthWallo">Dabub Wallo</t:settlement>
                    <t:location>
                        <t:geo>11.3388 39.6976</t:geo>
                        <t:height cert="medium">2,030 m</t:height>
                    </t:location>
                    <t:note>
                        <t:date type="foundation" cert="low" notBefore="0800" notAfter="1199">9th-12th
                            cent.</t:date>
                        <t:desc type="foundation">According to <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1467GadlaI">Gadla ʾIyasus Moʾā</t:ref> there were two
                            churches founded on the monastery's site. One was built around the <t:date notBefore="0900" notAfter="0999" cert="low">10th cent.</t:date> by <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS3493Delnaod">Dǝlnāʿod</t:persName> and <t:roleName type="title">ʾabuna</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS8386SalamaI">Salāmā</t:persName> and dedicated to God the
                            Father. The other one was founded in <t:date when="0862" cert="low">862
                                AD</t:date> (or <t:date when="1167">1167 AD</t:date> according to
                                <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS3076Cerulli">Cerulli</t:persName>'s chronology),
                            consecrated by <t:roleName type="title">Metropolitan</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS2668Benyam">Bǝnyam</t:persName> and dedicated to
                                <t:roleName type="title">Saint</t:roleName>
                            <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS8974Stephen">Stephen</t:persName>. However, <t:ref type="work" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/LIT1467GadlaI">Gadla ʾIyasus Moʾā</t:ref> are
                            very incoherent and their goal seems rather to be to place the monastery's
                            foundation before the <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10523Zagwe">Zāgʷe</t:persName>
                            dynasty.</t:desc>
                        <t:ab type="history">
                            <t:desc>The development of Dabra Ḥayq ʾƎsṭifānos began with the arrival of
                                    <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5633IyasusM">ʾIyasus Moʾā</t:persName> to the
                                island in approx. <t:date when="1248" precision="low">1248</t:date>. He
                                offered his support to <t:roleName type="title">ʾaṣe</t:roleName>
                                <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10303Yekunno">Yǝkunno ʾAmlāk</t:persName> to seize
                                the throne of the <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10523Zagwe">Zāgʷe</t:persName>.
                                The monastery became very close to the Ethiopian rulers and was richly
                                endowed with lands. Dabra Ḥayq ʾƎsṭifānos was destroyed and
                                looted by <t:persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS1522Ahmadb">ʾAḥmad b. ʾIbrāhīm
                                    al-Ġāzī</t:persName> in <t:date when="1532">1532</t:date>. However the
                                monastery continued to be an important religious centre throughout
                                the <t:date notBefore="1800" notAfter="1899">19th</t:date> and <t:date notBefore="1900" notAfter="1999">20th cent.</t:date> and has been
                                famous for its rich library.</t:desc>
                        </t:ab>
                        <t:ab type="description">The monastery of Dabra Ḥayq ʾƎsṭifānos is located on
                            the island of <t:placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3832Hayq">Lake Ḥayq</t:placeName>.
                        </t:ab>
                    </t:note>
